<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-499-498  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 499 498.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  May 28 1990 n272 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Treasury bids high-tech. (government automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kass, Elliot M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Treasury is automating its auction process, partly underpressure from the banks and investment houses that do businesswith it.andP;  The Treasury's Bureau of Public Debt sold $1.25 trillionin bonds, notes, and bills in 1989, all by hand.andP;  Automation willreduce the time it takes to report auction results from threehours to 10 minutes.andP;  The Public Securities Association (PSA),which represents the 44 principal dealers for the Federal ReserveBank of New York, pushed for the automated sales because the delayin reporting auction results causes market jitters.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyAutomationSecurities TransferUnited States. Department of the TreasuryPublic Securities Association.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>